<br>
I can tell you from experience that Anti Depressent medication isnt designed to make you &quot;happy&quot;. It is designed to correct an imbalance of chemicals so that a person can see the world from a place that isnt overly negative. <br>
<br>
Depression can be brutal. The serious type that requires medical (or professional) help is not a condition that one can simply &quot;shake off a bad mood&quot;. It is a condition that places a person in a state of mind where they are incapable (or nearly so) of viewing events, circumstances, and just general reality without it being close to overwelming, simple actions are viewed as overwelming events.<br>
<br>
I personally have never found an anti depressent that does more than help me fight the more severe aspects. I doubt that I will ever find one that will make me even consider life as worthwhile (no messages please, I will survive for now, been like this for all my life).<br>
<br>
Anti depressent medication is not designed to perk you up, or make you falsely happy. It is to allow enough chemicals to flow in your brain so that you may think and respond in a less depressed manner. And there is the problem... No one knows for sure exactly which chemicals cause exactly what. They do have many types now and it becomes a game of testing to see what one needs and how much they need.<br>
<br>
To further agrevate the process, most old line drugs and still most newer also, require several weeks (as much as 6 to 8 for some) to build up enough in a persons system to be properly evaluated. Also some people need more than one type of chemical. And some people simply can not be helped by medication (though most statistical studies indicate 80 percent plus can be).<br>
<br>
No responsible Doctor prescribes anti depressents for the purpose of making someone &quot;happy&quot;. That is a place an individual has to independantly find on their own.<br>
<br>
Though as noted, some more aggresive types of medication may cause a false sense of Euphoria if not properly administered.<br>
<br>
There are medications legally used to &quot;perk&quot; some one up. Though most have a side effect that can cause the opposite effect. I have taken anti depressents, mood adjustment medication, and medication designed to give one more 'energy&quot;.<br>
<br>
My experience is that if some one is not naturally &quot;happy&quot;, &quot;hyper&quot;, &quot;extreme&quot; or what ever term you want to use for higher than average... there is no Doctor that will actively prescribe medication to make them so. Anti depressents are not used to alter your reality, they are used to allow you to see it from a more balanced perspective. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/upalantiri.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Palantiri</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Woodfella</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/31/02 5:00:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Chances are ..</span><hr size=1> /agree with Twotribes. <br>
<br>
What is happiness really? I think it is different things to different people. Chemicals may induce temporary euphoria, but they aren't going to leave you happy. And if you were happy all the time, how would you know it? It would become the norm for you and then you wouldn't see it as anything special anymore. <br>
<br>
I think then that maybe happiness is fleeting and seldom, and it should be that way.<br>
